Dr. Baird is a highly motivated and talented operations research analyst with a Ph.D. in political science and expertise in matters involving the analysis of strategic systems, specifically: international political, military, economic, financial, social or related networks and their impact on U.S. National Security.  He is responsible for assisting in the coordination of issues and actions between U.S. Military Commanders and government officials at all levels. Additionally, he has written extensively on the impact of developing countries governance infrastructure on their economic outcomes and it's primacy over democracy in affecting FDI, trade and development; Major Power status and its effects on the international system; and the impact that U.S. supply chain vulnerabilities can and will have on national defense.

Between 1992 and 1997, I studied Biology and Chemistry at the University of Kaiserslautern (TU Kaiserslautern), Germany, and 1997 received the German Diploma in Biology (equivalent to M.S., with major focus on Genetics, Human Genetics and Organic Chemistry). For graduate training and doctoral research I moved to the Eberhard-Karls-University of Tübingen and the University Hospital of Tübingen, Germany, where I focused on Virology and Human Genetics, and received my Ph.D. degree (Dr.rer.nat., Doctorate in Natural Sciences) in 2002.

In 2002, I joined the University of Arizona (Arizona Cancer Center and College of Pharmacy, Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology) as post-doctoral research associate and received further training in Cancer Biology and Toxicology. Between 2005 and 2013, I worked as a Senior Research Investigator at the University of Pennsylvania, conducting research in the fields of Male Reproductive Biology and Toxicology. Since2013, I have been on the faculty at Utah State University in the Department of Animal, Dairy and Veterinary Sciences and the School of Veterinary Medicine, where I teach Veterinary Toxicology, Biotechnology (Cell Culture), Environmental Health and Epigenetics. The research focus of my lab is to find out how the environmental and nutritional environment of a male changes the quality and epigenetic information in his germ cells, and indirectly how healthy his offspring will be. My lab has developed a transgenic mouse model with humanized niacin requirements. This mouse permits us to study how nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) availability affects metabolic health and reproductive fitness through metabolic and epigenetic mechanisms.

Using my formal background in materials science and engineering along with  8+ years of  research experience, I am able to support R&D efforts focused on evaluating materials through fundamental material physics and science principles. Through my core competencies and applying the concepts of integrated computational materials engineering and materials informatics, I support efforts to characterize the physical properties of materials and identify/design novel materials while focusing on their potential technological impact. My passion for materials science and engineering runs deep, but I am also seriously invested in the engagement, collaboration, and building of productive relationships with other scientist and engineers.  

My core areas of expertise include:

Computational materials science 
Thermodynamics of materials
Structure-property relationships of materials
Physics of materials
Scientific programming

Badi H. Baltagi is distinguished Professor of Economics, and Senior Research Associate at the Center for Policy Research, The Maxwell School, Syracuse University since 2005. He received his Ph.D. in Economics at the University of Pennsylvania in 1979. He was George Summey, Jr. Professor of Liberal Arts, at Texas A&M University, 1993-2005.  Professor Baltagi was also visiting professor at the University of Arizona and the University of California, San Diego, and part-time chair at the University of Leicester, United Kingdom. He is the author of several books including: Econometric Analysis of Panel Data, 5th edition (2013, Wiley); and Econometrics, 5th edition (2011, Springer), and editor of A Companion to Theoretical Econometrics (2001, Blackwell); Recent Developments in the Econometrics of Panel Data, Volumes I and II (2002, Edward Elgar); Nonstationary Panels, Panel Cointegration, and Dynamic Panels (2000, Elsevier); Panel Data Econometrics: Critical Concepts in Economics, Four Volumes, (2015, Routledge, Taylor & Francis Group),and the Oxford Handbook of Panel Data (2015, Oxford University Press). He is also author or co-author of over 200 publications, all in leading economics journals, including: Econometrica, Journal of Econometrics, Journal of Political Economy, The Review of Economics and Statistics, International Economic Review, Econometric Theory, Journal of Applied Econometrics, and Journal of Business and Economic Statistics, to mention a few. Professor Baltagi is editor of Economics Letters, and associate editor of Econometric Reviews. He was also editor of Empirical Economics, (1999-2018), Associate editor of Journal of Econometrics (1999-2018) and the replication editor for the Journal of Applied Econometrics (2003-2018). He is a fellow of the Journal of Econometrics as well as Econometric Reviews and a recipient of the Multa and Plura Scripsit Awards from Econometric Theory. Also fellow of the Advances in Econometrics and recipient of the Distinguished Authors Award from the Journal of Applied Econometrics. He is a Founding fellow and member of the Board of Directors of the Spatial Econometrics Association. He is also a Founding Member and ex-director of the International Association for Applied Econometrics. He also received the Distinguished Achievement Award in Research, from the Association of Former Students, at Texas A&M University (2002). He was also the 2018 winner of the Kuwait Prize for Economics and Social Sciences.

Sahar Aghasafari is an Art and Graphic Design Assistant Professor at the University of South Carolina Lancaster. As an art educator and visual artist, her research focuses on interdisciplinary visual/media arts and science studies. She seeks to identify productive ways to integrate visual/media arts into STEM to support students’ academic achievement. Sahar holds a BFA in Fabrics Design from the University of Tehran, two masters’ in Art Education from the University of Arizona and Art Research from the University of Tehran, and a Ph.D. in Art Education from the University of Georgia.

Dr. Megan McDonald completed her PhD in 2012 in the Phytopathology Group at the ETH Zürich in Switzerland. After completing her PhD she was awarded a Swiss National Science Foundation Fellowship to take-up post-doctoral work in the genomics of plant pathogens at the Australian National University in Canberra, Australia. In Australia she was funded by wheat growers to continue her work on the genomics of fungal plant pathogens, looking specifically at genome plasticity and fungicide resistance. In 2020, Megan was awarded a Birmingham Fellowship to start her own research group at the University of Birmingham.

Kolby Jardine studies plant and microbial metabolism by working at the interface of biochemistry, ecology, and atmospheric sciences (Biochemical Ecology) and is a research scientist in the Ecology Department within the Climate & Ecosystem Sciences Division of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.

The primary goal of the research is to characterize quantitative relationships between biochemical, optical, and volatile organic signals emitted by plants during climate extremes in order to characterize processes and mechanisms of potentially high global importance. This presents exciting opportunities for the development of new methods for the continuous local and global monitoring of the physiological, energetic, and oxidative status of plants and ecosystems and their associated cycling of carbon and water.

Field, greenhouse, and laboratory methods are developed for the quantification of carbon dioxide and gas-phase volatile organic compound concentrations, fluxes, and isotopic composition from leaves to ecosystems and seconds to seasons. Methods include IR spectrometry, proton transfer reaction mass spectrometry (PTR-MS), and thermal desorption-gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (TD-GC-MS).

Current Projects
1) Working with Phase 2 of the Next Generation Ecosystem Experiments (NGEE) Tropics project in the Brazilian Amazon, Kolby installed an isotope trace gas laboratory and maintains a small research group at the National Institute for Amazon Research in Manaus, Brazil to study photosynthesis, respiration, and defense. Prior to returning to Berkeley Lab, he was based in Manaus where he led the BrazilianAIR campaign (5 mo), the terrestrial ecosystem component of the GoAmazon project (4 yr), and NGEE Tropics Phase I (2 yr).

2) Together with postdoc Rebecca Dewhirst and collaborators at the Joint Bioenergy Institute (JBEI) and Environmental Molecular Sciences Laboratory (EMSL), a DOE BER early career research project (ECRP) is underway entitled, “O-Acetylation and methylation engineering of plant cell walls for enhanced biofuel production”. Also known as the poplar esterified cell wall transformations and metabolic integration (PECTIN) study, this project studies the metabolism of cell wall esters and their roles in forest response to climate in the emerging biofuel tree species California poplar (Populus trichocarpa).

3) Exploring the role of volatile organic compounds in soil biogeochemistry.

Professor Marie Wilson is the former Chief Academic Services Officer of the University of South Australia and former Pro Vice Chancellor (Business and Law). Her research areas span decision making and performance in a number of clinical and professional contexts. Professor Wilson is on sabbatical in 2022.

Professor Wilson holds a Juris Doctor (JD) in contract and employment law, a PhD in management and has over twenty years of university leadership experience, as well as extensive industry experience in IT and services.

department_name: Pediatrics, Pediatric Pulmonary and Sleep Medicine

biography:
Research focus:
* Spatial and temporal interactions of large mammals with variable resources: foraging, habitat, demography, and abundance
* Quantitative methods to estimate and model abundance, demography and distribution of animal populations
* Wildlife management and capacity building in transboundary regions.

I am accepting applications for post-graduate research in the field of quantitative population ecology and, in particular, Bayesian analysis and hierarchical modelling. If you are interested in post-graduate research in my lab, please send (1) a current CV, (2) contact details for three references, (3) copies of your university transcripts, (4) a letter of motivation, and (5) a concept statement. The letter should detail the research topic that interests you, why you think my lab is the place to pursue it, and how you would incorporate quantitative methods into your research.  For the concept statement, write about a potential research project that is of interest to you.  Make it no more than two pages, include references, and show me how well you think and write about wildlife science.

Teaching: 3rd-year applied population ecology, 4th-year study design and data analysis,  4th-year wildlife population analysis

Biomedical researcher/faculty focusing on drug development and biomarker analysis in colorectal cancer and other solid tumors primarily. Current focuses are on target identification and combinatorial immunotherapeutics (including CAR T-cells).

Esjay Wonderly is a transmedia producer with previous experience in documentary production and film marketing. She earned her MFA in Interactive Media from the University of Southern California’s School of Cinematic Arts and is obsessed with creating participatory experiences that promote narrative agency and humanist ideals.

Following a double graduation in Engineering at the Institut d'Optique Graduate School (Palaiseau, France) and in a Master of Science at the University of Arizona (Tucson, AZ, USA), my professional career began in March 2012 with my PhD at the CNRS Laboratory of Photonics and Nanostructures (LPN which will be transformed in June 2016 into the Center of Nanosciences and Nanotechnologies C2N). My work under the supervision of Stéphane COLLIN focused on the optical trapping of light in ultra-thin layers (100-200 nm) of GaAs. Additional improvements on this technology led to records of absorption and conversion efficiencies on ultrathin solar cells (see Chen et al. publications below). 

Once I obtained my PhD degree from the University of Paris-Sud (now Paris-Saclay) in 2015, I worked for IPVF as a 6-month postdoc, mostly devoted to the application of nanophotonic concepts developed during my thesis for new concepts of up-conversion or hot carrier solar cells. 

Driven by a strong interest in the economics of the PV sector, I continued to work at  IPVF in 2016 by joining the "PV economy" project  alongside Denis JAHAN. I was specifically involved in the development of a common vision of the PV market shared by all our partners and I developed cost models for various PV technologies. I also worked on ways to enforce the value of the Institute's research projects.

Then I joined in 2017 a consulting firm specialized in innovation financing where I was in charge of a portfolio containing around 30 companies, mostly SMEs.

I returned to IPVF in 2020 with the mission of maintaining the prototyping part of the technological platform (10+ research tools) and developing fablab capabilities at IPVF.

I work on the algebraic and combinatorial structures associated with walks on graphs as well as similar objects such as primitive orbits, self-avoiding walks and hikes. My main interest lies in developing a "theory of walks" independent from graph theory and relying on number theory. The later arises from the recognition that hikes (which are formally heaps of graph cycles) obey a very natural semi-commutative extension of number theory.
Academic and research interests focus on the interaction of attention and movement control in rehabilitation, using dual- and multi-tasking paradigms in adults with neurological injury, and disease.

Dr. Haytham Wali is a board-certified infectious disease pharmacist and a clinical assistant professor of infectious diseases pharmacotherapy in the Department of Pharmacy Practice at King Faisal University College of Clinical Pharmacy in Al-Ahsa, Saudi Arabia. He completed his Doctor of Pharmacy (PharmD) degree at King Abdulaziz University Faculty of Pharmacy in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, in 2011. Then, he completed the Certificate of Advanced Pharmacy Practice Studies (CAPPS) program at MCPHS University in Boston, Massachusetts, United States, in 2015, and the Advanced Clinical Pharmacy Practice Graduate Certificate program at The University of Arizona College of Pharmacy in Tucson, Arizona, United States, in 2018. He did his Post-graduate Year One (PGY1) pharmacy residency at Carondelet St. Joseph’s Hospital in Tucson, Arizona, United States, in 2020. Finally, he did his PGY2 infectious diseases residency at Piedmont Columbus Regional in Columbus, Georgia, United States, in 2021. His areas of interest include antimicrobial stewardship, antimicrobial resistance, and clinical microbiology. Dr. Wali is a member of the American College of Clinical Pharmacy (ACCP), the Infectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA), the Society of Infectious Diseases Pharmacists (SIDP), the American Society of Health-system Pharmacists (ASHP), and the Saudi Society of Clinical Pharmacy (SSCP).

Associate Professor, University of Melbourne for most of the year and Visiting Professor, Lancaster Environment Centre, Lancaster University [was full time Professor there, 2017-2019]. 
Environment and development specialist, editor of Journal of Political Ecology since 2003, occasional research on bicycles in cities, higher education policy.
All research to make change, not advance career.

I have created an innovative research program during my 28+ year career, including 21 years at the University of Florida, and since 2019, at the University of Arizona.  My work spans several cross-disciplinary research areas, including energy and spectroscopy, but primarily in the area of laser-based diagnostics, laser-material interactions, and biophotonics.  With the latter, I develop and apply laser-based sensing schemes to study applications from medicine to environmental monitoring, including early work on laser corneal ablation (early version of LASIK).  Since my time at Sandia, I have worked on a technique called laser-induced breakdown spectroscopy (LIBS), a laser-based sensing scheme applicable to direct analysis of solids, liquids, gases and aerosols.  My LIBS work addresses practical applications in combination with understanding the physics of the relevant transport processes.  Recent work involves a method we call differential laser-induced perturbation spectroscopy.  Other areas of interest include classical light scattering and Raman spectroscopy.

I have broad interests in various biology questions. My current research interests include: 1) adaptive evolution of genes; 2) dynamics and mechanisms of the widespread distribution of retrotransposons; 3) identification of imprinting genes in maize and its dynamic expression patterns during early seed development; 4) evolution of alternative splicing process. My long-term goal is to understand: 1) what and how the fitness landscape of molecules shape or direct the evolution of species; 2) to introduce advanced mathematical theory, such as group theory, matrix analysis to illustrate the subtle map between "life phenomenon" and "numbers".

My research utilizes self-assembly, molecular design, and microfluidic technologies to generate biologically relevant microenvironments for the study and application of biomacromolecules. Individually, microfluidics represent an enabling technology for the time-resolved analysis of enzyme structural dynamics, while control over molecular interactions in self-assembling polyelectrolyte systems can be used to examine the interplay between biomacromolecules and the intracellular environment. Together, these capabilities can be coupled to generate artificial organelle-like structures for use in applications ranging from biochemistry to bioenergetics, biocatalysis, and biomedicine. Furthermore, this work has tremendous pedagogical potential to inspire students to work at the intersection of chemistry, biology, and engineering.

At the moment Gisele occupies the post of Teaching Fellow/Portuguese Teaching Associate (Brazilian Leitora) at the Department of Modern Languages of the University of Birmingham, UK (2020-2024). She holds a Postdoctoral (2019-2020) degree in Translation Studies at Universidade Federal de Santa Catarina, a BA (1992) in Comunicação Social – Jornalismo from Faculdades Integradas Helio Alonso (FACHA – RJ), a Master's degree (2010) and a Ph.D. (2014) in Translation Studies, and a Letras/Inglês BA (2017/2018) from Universidade Federal de Santa Catarina (UFSC). In this same institution, she was a tutor in Textual Production in the Portuguese pedagogical and educational guidance program (2012-13), and at the moment integrates extension projects: Núcleo de Pesquisa e Ensino em Português Língua Estrangeira (NUPLE), Português sem Fronteiras (MEC), and Cursos Extracurriculares de Línguas – Portuguese, Japanese and English. Throughout her academic life, Gisele has published articles mostly in the field of Translation Studies; Japanese Language, Literature, and Culture; and more recently language acquisition and Portuguese as a Second Language. Scholarship awards from the Japanese Foundation (2011) and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan (2016). My research interests are in the area of translation studies and language teaching, focusing on the intersection of language, translation, and culture, working mainly with the following themes: Translation between literature and other media, including animation movies; audiovisual translation; children's literature; translation and culture; paratexts and (para)translation; and translation and lexicography. She is currently responsible for the design and implementation of the Digital First project, for the Portuguese course of the Languages for All Programme, as part of the IWLP (Institution-wide Languages Program of the UK).

Margaret (Maggie) Kiel-Morse joined Indiana Law in July 2019 as the faculty services librarian. She is responsible for reviewing and updating the Library’s faculty services policies, including managing the research request and current awareness services, and routinely reaching out to faculty and clinics. She also supervises the Library’s Faculty Research Assistant Program, and conducts an orientation workshop for students hired as RAs. Maggie is part of the Library’s strong team of librarians providing legal research instruction for 1L and Advanced Legal Research classes, in addition to any other instructional sessions upon request. She also provides reference services for the Law School's faculty and students, the greater IU community, and the public.

Originally hailing from Cleveland, Ohio, Maggie began her law library career in 2009 while a student at Michigan State University College of Law. After completing her JD, she continued on to the Law Library Fellowship Program at the University of Arizona, earning a master’s in library and information science.

Dr Supitcha Chanyotha is currently working for Nuclear Engineering Department, Faculty of Engineering, Chulalongkorn University (CU) in Bangkok, Thailand, as Professor Position. She is responsible for nuclear education and research work at CU.

Christopher A. Miller (MA, University of Arizona; MM, Northern Illinois University; BA, University of North Carolina School of the Arts) is a musician, archivist, digital collections manager, non-Roman cataloger, computational humanist, and information consultant living in the Blue Ridge mountains of Virginia. Christopher currently serves as Digital Humanities Coordinator for the University Libraries at Virginia Tech. He has been traveling and conducting research in Southeast Asia for the past 19 years, with extended living periods in both Indonesia and Burma/Myanmar. Christopher has previously worked as Southeast Asian Studies Bibliographer for Arizona State University Libraries; Curator of e-kiNETx and Cross-Cultural Dance Resources in Arizona State University's School of Dance; Curator of Audiovisual Collections for the Musical Instrument Museum; and University Archivist at Radford University. His graduate work in ethnomusicology in Indonesia (Java) and Myanmar (Yangon and Taunggyi) later expanded into an interest in the role of libraries, archives, and museums in the representation of culture and the performing arts, especially among minority populations. Christopher's audiovisual and document digitization projects have been funded by the U.S. State Department Ambassador's Fund for Cultural Preservation (early Burmese recordings); the British Library Endangered Archives Programme (Pa'O manuscript archive and the same early Burmese recordings); the National Science Foundation (Tai linguistics sound archives of William Gedney with Prof. Thomas J. Hudak); and the Center for Burma Studies (field recordings of Muriel Williamson).

Narsireddy Anugu currently works at the CHARA Array as Optical Systems Scientist. Before that Anugu pursued two postdoc fellowships at the University of Arizona and the University Exeter/Michigan. Anugu earned his Ph.D. from University of Porto by involving in the successful development of VLTI/GRAVITY in 2017 working. GRAVITY has contributed several interesting science results including 2020 Nobel Prize Physics.

PhD in Computer Science from State Federal University of Rio de Janeiro
PhD in Administration from Fundação Getúlio Vargas
Master in Business Administration from COPPEAD Institute of Administration / Federal University of Rio de Janeiro
Graduate Certificate in Systems Engineering
Bachelor degree in Business Administration from the Universidade Federal Rural do Rio de Janeiro
Bachelor degree in Information Systems from Open School in Brazil


Teaching experience in the Rural Federal University of Rio de Janeiro and the University of Cape Verde (West Africa). Reviewer of international journals. Getulio Vargas Foundation consultant in consulting projects for the Federal Government, specifically to the Ministry of Finance within the Ministry of Finance Modernization Program, including implementation of project management offices and processes, management model enterprise risk model public company information and preparation technology relationship for certification to ISO 9001 Researcher of FGV in on entrepreneurship projects, public finance and e-government. Consulting experience in the public and private sector, working on projects in Brazil, Colombia, Cape Verde and the United States in various sectors and industries. Skills include project management, design and implementation of management models, analysis and design processes, indicators and dashboards, statistical models and data analysis.

Dr. Koehler is the CEO of Visual Data Analytics and a certified professional hydrologist with over 40-years’ experience.

Previously he was the National Hydrologic and Geospatial Sciences Training Coordinator for NOAA’s National Weather Service and is a retired NOAA Corps lieutenant commander. Assignments included navigation and operations officer for two NOAA oceanographic research ships, the Colorado Basin River Forecast Center and the Northwest River Forecast Center where he oversaw the implementation of an operational dynamic wave model for Lower Columbia River stage forecasts. Other positions include Director of Water Resources for an Arizona consulting company and the water resources hydrologist for Cochise County, Arizona. 

He is also a member of the science department faculty at Front Range Community College and is instructor for astronomy, geology, geography, GIS and geodesy courses. He is also an FAA certified professional drone operator.

He has a PhD, MS and BS in Watershed Management from the University of Arizona and an additional MS in Hydrographic Sciences from the US Naval Postgraduate School. The focus of his research are alternate methods of analyzing environmental time-series data along with associated data visualizations.

Ryane E. Englar, DVM, DABVP (Canine and Feline Practice) is a 2008 graduate of Cornell University College of Veterinary Medicine. Following graduation, she spent five years as an associate veterinarian in small animal practice, split between her home state of Maryland and her home-away-from-home, upstate New York.  She then became a Clinical Instructor of the Community Practice Service at Cornell’s Companion Animal Hospital and a Consultant for the Louis J. Camuti Hotline in association with Cornell’s Feline Health Center. 

In February 2014, Dr. Englar relocated to Arizona, where she was privileged to be founding faculty for Midwestern University College of Veterinary Medicine. As an Assistant Professor of Small Animal Primary Care, she designed and debuted the communications coursework for the inaugural class of 2018. By developing 27 standardized client encounters over eight pre-clinical quarters, she was able to expand the breadth and depth of standardized client encounters in the veterinary curriculum. Her experiences in simulation-based education have been detailed in her active publication history with the Journal of Veterinary Medical Education. 

Dr. Englar joined the faculty at Kansas State University in May 2017 to build the clinical skills curriculum for first and second year veterinary students. Her coursework emphasizes hands-on training with the opportunity for practice and repetition to build those clinical and professional skills that promote Day-One-Ready graduates. Her interests in the design and development of non-animal teaching models have led her and her team to create novel learning opportunities for her students.

Dr. Englar joined the faculty of the University of Arizona College of Veterinary Medicine in February 2020 to design and debut the Clinical and Professional Skills series of courses in August 2020, when the Inaugural Class of 2023 arrives on campus.

When she is not teaching or brainstorming new approaches to learning, she is a competitive ballroom dancer and artist.

Aurelien Manchon is an Associate Professor of Materials Science and Engineering at the King Abdullah University of Science and Technology, in Saudi Arabia. He joined KAUST in 2009 after a postdoctoral fellowship at University of Missouri-Columbia and University of Arizona-Tuscon. He graduated from the Ecole Polytechnique, Palaiseau, France in 2004 and earned his PhD in Physics in 2007 from University Joseph Fourier and CEA/SPINTEC laboratory in France. Manchon’s research focuses on spintronics, which aims at utilizing the quantum spin degree of freedom of the carrier to generate disruptive solutions for electronics. His research interest spans from spin-orbit coupled transport to chiral magnetism, antiferromagnets and ultrafast spin dynamics. Manchon has engaged in a number of collaborations with both experimentalists and theorists in his field around the world, including researchers at National University of Singapore, CEA/CNRS Grenoble in France, Johannes Gutenberg University in Mainz, Germany, Cornell University, University of Minnesota, Tokyo University etc. He has authored over 100 publications in esteemed journals including Nature, Nature Materials, Nature Physics, Physical Review Letters, Nano Letters, Physical Review B, and Applied Physics Letters.

Dr Robert Simpson is a staff physiatrist at the Toronto Rehabilitation Institute. Besides specialist training and certification in Rehabilitation Medicine and General Practice, he has post graduate fellowship training in Integrative Medicine.

Dr Simpson has methods expertise in:

    Epidemiology
    Systematic reviews and meta-analyses
    Qualitative meta-aggregation
    Clinical trials
    Qualitative research methods

I am an Associate Professor of Geography, Environment and Society, and Institute on the Environment Fellow at the University of Minnesota. I'm also a Humboldt Research Fellow at the Alexander von Humboldt Foundation (Germany) and an Adjunct Assistant Professor in the School of Environmental Sciences at Queen’s University (Canada).
 
As an earth scientist trained in paleoclimatology, I use evidence preserved in geological or biological archives to understand how and why our environment has changed during the last several hundred or thousands of years. By extending our perspective beyond the most recent century, my research provides a long-term benchmark to test ideas about the underlying causes of environmental change and the likely future trajectories of critical environmental systems, particularly those aspects related to forests, climate change, and surface hydrology.
I am Dean of Libraries at Northeastern Illinois University.

Vinícius P. Gonçalves has a Ph.D. in Computer Science and Computational Mathematics (2016) from the University of São Paulo (USP). He was also a research fellow at the University of Arizona (USA) before joining the University of Brasília (UnB). Dr. Gonçalves was a Postdoctoral Researcher at the USP Medical School, with a CAPES Fellowship. Currently, he is an Assistant Professor in the Department of Electrical Engineering (ENE) at UnB, Brasília, Brazil, where he is a member of the Graduate Programs in Electrical Engineering (PPGEE and PPEE). Dr. Gonçalves is a researcher and member of the AQUARELA Group; his main research interests include Human–Computer Interaction, Internet of Things, Cybersecurity, Mobile Health, Image Processing and Machine Learning.

Thilo M. Brill is a physicist at the Schlumberger-Riboud Product Centre (SRPC), Clamart, France. He is currently involved in the design and development of ultrasound instruments for oilfield-service logging-while drilling applications. He obtained his doctorate in physics is from the University of Konstanz, Germany. After a postdoctoral research at Harvard University, he joined Schlumberger in 1998 in the magnetic resonance group at Schlumberger-Doll Research Center in Ridgefield, CT (USA). Five years later he became an engineering physicist at SRPC, where he contributed to several projects in the fields of electromagnetic and ultrasonic nondestructive casing and cement evaluation for downhole wireline and drilling & measurement applications. During an interim period at the Schlumberger Princeton Technology Center in New Jersey (USA) he managed the development of nuclear detectors for several downhole tools. He is interested in applications of state-of-the art ultrasonic, electromagnetic and optical sensor technologies in the context of harsh downhole environments and/or renewable energy resources.
Modeling and remote sensing of the terrestrial and global water cycles; global change impacts on water availability; remote sensing of groundwater and terrestrial water storage

Heather F. Smith a Professor in the Department of Anatomy at Midwestern University and the Editor-in-Chief of The Anatomical Record. She has a Ph.D. in Biological Anthropology (Arizona State University, 2008), M.A. in Biological Anthropology (Stony Brook University, 2003), and B.A. in Anthropology (Arizona State University, 2001). She completed her postdoctoral training at the University of Arizona College of Medicine—Phoenix (2009). She is an evolutionary biologist, anatomist, and paleontologist whose research focuses on the evolution and functional morphology of turtles, carnivorans, primates, and other mammals.

My research interests include plant conservation, floristics, and systematics of various groups of ferns and parasitic angiosperms. However, these days my job is mainly administrative, as the curator of herbaria at the Billie L. Turner Plant Resources Center at the Uiversity of Texas at Austin.  The TEX and LL herbaria there contain more than one million specimens and, like many museums worldwide, we devote a lot of effort to digitizing our resources to share them online with the world.

Dan T Nguyen joined Corning Research and Developmemt Inc. (Corning, New York) in February 2017 from College of Optical Sciences, The University of Arizona, where he was Associate Research Professor, and Adjunct Professor of the University of Arizona since 02/2017.
  
Dan T Nguyen received his PhD in 1993 from Institute of Physics, National Academy of Sciences, Hanoi, Vietnam, on theory of nonlinear optics in semiconductors. Since then, he has worked in several international academic institutions, and in photonics industry. He was a Visiting Researcher of the International Center for Theoretical Physics (ICTP), Trieste, Italy (3 months each year 1992, 1994, 1996, 1997) where he was elected as a Regular Associate Member (5-year term from 1995 to 2000); DAAD Research Fellow at Institut fur Festkorpertheorie und Theoretische Optik, Friedrich-Schiller-Universitat, Jena, Germany (8/1994 to 4/1995); Nishina Memorial Postdoc Fellow, Tokyo University (4/1995-6/1996), Chair of Theoretical Physics, Hue University, Vietnam (from 7/1996 to 7/1998), College of Optical Sciences, U of Arizona (Tucson, Arizona) from 1998 to 2017 from Research Associate to Associate Research Professor, and since 02/2017 as Adjunct Research Professor. He also worked as Principal Modeling Scientist, NP Photonics Inc., Tucson, Arizona

Surya Saha, PhD, is a computational biologist. He has a background in computer science, databases, omics analysis and biological data management. Over a career spanning more than ten years, he has worked with cross-matrixed teams of geneticists, molecular biologists, engineers, product development managers and software developers on a range of genomics, metabolomics, proteomics, metagenomics, microbiome and transcriptomics projects. He is a result-oriented bioinformatics scientist accomplished in leadership, project management, data integration and mining with a history of building strategic relationships with internal and external research labs and teams.

Dr. Saha has led a number of multi-institutional plant, microbial and arthropod omics projects. Most notably, he established the community data and analysis portal for citrusgreening research. He also leads the AgriVectors project that is a part of Phytobiomes initiative and is focused on arthropod vectors of agricultural diseases.

He recently joined the Public Programs team at Seven Bridges to develop technical strategies for empowering the use of standards by platform users and representing Seven Bridges’ interest at community standard meetings, guiding development through participation in development/oversight committees.

Current: Major Nicholas Lee is an Organizational Research and Systems Analysis (ORSA) Officer for the Data Science Directorate (DSD) within the U.S. Army’s Network and Communications Command (NETCOM) at Fort Huachuca Arizona. He performs high level data analytics on a variety of topics relating to NETCOM. Provides expert analysis to the director and customers on a variety of areas including operations research, network operations, applied statistics, machine learning, artificial intelligence, prediction, and general research and mathematics.

Career Path: Major Nicholas lee commissioned through the U.S. Army Officer Candidate School (OCS) in 2006 as an Infantry 2nd Lieutenant. After completion of OCS, Airborne School, Stryker Leaders Course, Mortar Leaders Course, Ranger School, and Reconnaissance and Surveillance Leaders Course, he was stationed with the Second Stryker Calvary Regiment (2SCR) in Vilseck Germany as an Infantry Platoon Leader. He served on deployment to Iraq with 2SCR from 2007 through 2008. Upon returning from Iraq, Major Lee served as the Executive Officer of Alpha Company Warrior Transition Unit located in Landstuhl Germany. Major Lee then was granted a branch transfer to Military Intelligence where he attended the Military intelligence Captains Career Course (MICCC). Upon completion of the MICCC he took Company Command of Charlie Company 206th Military Intelligence Battalion (Task Force ODIN) At Fort Hood Texas. After completion of Company Command, Major Lee deployed with TF ODIN to Afghanistan as the Brigade Intelligence Officer and later was awarded the position of the Analyst Control Element (ACE) Chief. Upon returning from Afghanistan, Major Lee was asked to participate in the U.S. Army’s Warrior program and teach intelligence preparation of the battlefield at the MICCC. Major Lee became the MICCC Chief where he was again awarded a voluntary transfer to the ORSA community. Upon acceptance, he was selected to attend the Naval Post Graduate School from 2017 through 2019. After graduation, Major Lee was assigned as a Data Scientist for the Data Science Directorate within NECTOM at Fort Huachuca.

Recent and Relevant Work: Approximately 15 months ago, Major Lee graduated from the Naval Post graduate School. A list of curricula taken to fulfill his degree requirements may be found at the following link: https://nps.smartcatalogiq.com/en/Current/Academic-Catalog/Graduate-School-of-Operational-and-Information-Sciences-GSOIS/Department-of-Operations-Research/Operations-Analysis-Curriculum-360 His thesis included statistical machine learning methodologies which may be viewed here: https://calhoun.nps.edu/handle/10945/62268 Approximately 6 months ago Major Lee graduated from the American Military University for which the curricula may be found at the following link:https://www.amu.apus.edu/academic/schools/security-and-global-studies/masters/intelligence-studies.html#requirements He is currently in the process of publishing a peer reviewed article within the Journal of defense Analytics and Logistics. Recently, Major Lee led the DSD data challenge team to place in the top 3, for the second year in a row, to a first and third place, respectively, standing out of 40 teams ~ 180 participants whom are data science professionals (Army wide FA49 Data Challenge).

Military Education: Infantry Officers Basic Course, Airborne School, Stryker Leaders Course, Mortar Leaders Course, Ranger School, Military intelligence Captains Career Course, Geospatial Intelligence Officers Course, Signal Intelligence Officers Course, ORSA Qualification (Q) Course.

Educational Degrees:
2020, American Military University, Master of Arts, Intelligence and National Security.
2019, Naval Postgraduate School, Master of Science, Operational Research and Systems Analysis with Data Analysis Certification.
2005, Westminster College, Bachelors of Science, Major: Pre-Medical Studies.

Awards: Bronze Star, Meritorious Service Medal, Army Commendation Medal (4), Army Achievement Medal (2), National defense Service Medal, Iraq Campaign Medal, Global War on Terrorism Service Medal, Army Service Ribbon, Overseas Service Ribbon, NATO Medal.

I am a Postdoctoral fellow at the USDA Methods and Application of Food Composition Lab

I work on various open source ontologies to promote food and life-science data interoperability.

I am a public health, clinical pharmacist. My interests are to improve health services through quality improvement and practice-based research. I work with an underserved population in a rural, clinical outpatient setting. My practice focuses on those with diabetes, asthma, and/or cardiology with respect to pharmacotherapy management and patient self-management education.

My long-term research interest is to understand the intercellular communication signals that regulate vascular remodeling, and to further determine how these signals may be dysregulated in diseases of the cardiovascular system. Specifically, I have focused on endothelial gap junction proteins (connexins, Cx) and have helped elucidate a crucial role for them in vascular growth and remodeling during development and disease. I have described a novel, flow-sensitive Notch-Cx37-p27 signaling axis in endothelial cells that enables arterial specification during blood vessel development. I have further shown that Cx37 deletion profoundly rescues post-ischemic injury vascular growth and remodeling while Cx40 is necessary for this process. I also helped show that Cx43 supports endothelial cell proliferation, as well as recruitment and differentiation of perivascular cells, although this function is also supported by Cx45. Taken together, these data underscore a critical role for gap junction proteins in growth regulation of the vasculature, and I intend to continue this research on connexins in vessel remodeling with my current and future work. I recently helped to develop a microphysiological model of vascular malformation in Hereditary Hemorragic Telangiectasia, and my future work will explore how Cx37, Cx40, and Cx43 are dysregulated leading to defects in cell-cell communication in vessel remodeling and arteriovenous malformation.

I am a senior scientist with 10+ years of experience designing, conducting and executing projects in various departments and institutions. I work with interdisciplinary teams, and I teach and mentor students in lecture-based and research-based content. Other than managing people and projects, I have extensive data anlysis experience, as well as writing experience. I enjoy writing grants and technical content for both, scientists and broad audiences, as well as creating graphical content to illustrate science (such as publication-quality and grant-level figures). My work for the past decade has been centered around microbiology and virology, with special focus on understanding how viruses control and manipulate the host cells they infect in the "live" stage of the virus called the "virocell".

Jay Morreale is an entrepreneurial professional with more than thirty years of experience in research, development, system design & integration, production, and test of commercial and high-reliability electro-optic systems, along with expertise in constructing proof-of-concept prototypes to support technical, business, and customer objectives. Through his small business, p-brane LLC, he provides electronic prototyping, modeling, analysis, design, research and development, and networking consulting services. Some of his past projects include an undersea power and communication junction box for an undersea observatory application, fiber optic delay line, an undersea transceiver design study, a medium voltage power supply and actuator driver, and adapting software to control a 6 axis alignment robot. Before consulting, Jay worked at AT&T bell laboratories and Lucent Technologies designing undersea telecommunication and optical networking hardware. He co-founded Red Sky Systems which made regional undersea systems unit. Jay earned a Bachelors and Masters in Electrical Engineering from the University of Arizona. When not consulting, he is developing a graphene based terahertz light source for communication and spectroscopy applications which has been awarded two patents. To learn more, see my profile on LinkedIn linkedin.com/in/pbrane

Roberta is a second-year graduate student in the library and information sciences program at the University of Arizona. She is also a professional technologist and information strategist. Her work focuses on content analysis, social and behavioral analysis, and storytelling to deliver audience-focused experiences. Roberta has assisted research efforts in environmental science, climate change, and landscape stewardship while also working with technological innovations in the cultural-heritage fields. Her current interest lies in researching the interactions of factual information dissemination, environmental sustainability, economics, and industrial sociology as they relate innovations for social change.

biography:
I attended Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons for medical school, where I began my research career with Dr. Hiroo Takayama analyzing single center outcomes of temporary mechanical circulatory support in cardiogenic shock. Staying at Columbia for  internal medicine residency, I began to focus my efforts on clinical research in durable left ventricular assist device therapies as bridge to heart transplantation. Working with Dr. Veli Topkara and Dr. Maryjane Farr, I was the first author of multiple publications highlighting the nationwide variability in the use of this listing strategy as well as implications of ventricular assist device support on early post-transplant outcomes. I began to focus, particularly, on the risk of primary graft dysfunction in patients bridged to transplant with these devices, and after publishing our single center results, I worked with colleagues from Stanford University to develop the International Consortium on Primary Graft Dysfunction: an international, observational cohort of over 2500 heart transplant recipients from the United State and Europe. Leveraging this large and well-phenotyped population, we have been able to, for the first time, define clinical risk factors for primary graft dysfunction in the contemporary era and demonstrate that older risk scoring systems no long adequately capture donor and recipient risk.  

The move to Duke for cardiology fellowship was a natural one, given the strong reputation of Duke Cardiology in translational and basic cardiovascular research. Moreover, the Duke fellowship offered unparalleled research opportunities for its trainees by providing a minimum of two years of funded research under its NIH T32 training grants. I was very fortunate to meet with Dr. Svati Shah early on in my fellowship and developed a plan to spend my dedicated research time in her lab learning more about multiomic profiling and how it may be applied in the heart transplant space. During my dedicated research time and given my clinical interests in primary graft dysfunction, I designed and executed a project to define pre-transplant biomarkers of primary graft dysfunction in a large, well-phenotyped cohort of heart transplant recipients. We found a novel biomarker, CLEC4C, to be increased in the circulation of recipients who would go on to develop moderate to severe primary graft dysfunction and validated these signals in a separate cohort, even after adjustment for other important clinical covariates. This work has been published in the Journal of Heart and Lung Transplantation. We submitted additional abstracts leveraging mass spectroscopy based proteomics for biomarkers of graft dysfunction in static cold storage preservation solution and also highlighted circulating pre-transplant proteins that were associated with post-transplant renal failure. Finally, we recently received funding to perform single cell RNA sequencing on myocardial tissue from heart explanted for severe cardiac allograft vasculopathy to examine the transcriptomic landscape of chronic allograft rejection. During my time at Duke I was fortunate to receive an NIH Loan Repayment Award and Renewal as well as a Mandel Family Foundation Award, a Translating Duke Health grant, and a Duke Transplant Center Pilot Award. I was also the recipient of the Joseph Greenfield Research Scholar Award which provided additional salary support and a research stipend. During my research time at Duke I completed a Masters in Biostatistics through the Duke University School of Medicine. 


The experiences above have solidified my desire to pursue a career as an academic physician-scientist in advanced heart failure cardiology. I have recently transitioned to the University of Texas Southwestern as an Advanced Heart Failure and Transplant fellow, where I am continuing my work leveraging omics technologies to better understand and characterize post-transplant outcomes.

Jorge Lemus is a linguist working in the documentation, maintenance, and revitalization of endangered languages.  He received his Ph.D. in Linguistics from the University of Arizona, with a specialization in phonology and linguistic anthropology. He is currently a linguistics professor and researcher in the School of Languages and Education at University Don Bosco (UDB), El Salvador. He is also the director and editor of Científica, a multidisciplinary scientific journal. He has been codirector of the PhD program in Social Sciences and director of research at UDB. In addition, he has been a professor at Universidad de El Salvador and a visiting professor at Penn State University, the University of the Basque Country, the University of Sonora, California State University at Sacramento and the Public University of Navarra. He has been a guest lecturer in several European countries, Japan, Israel, USA, Mexico, Central and South America. He is a founding member of the Central American Association of Linguistics and he is currently deputy director of the Salvadoran Academy of Language, corresponding to the Royal Spanish Academy.  In 2010, he was awarded El Salvador's National Culture Prize for his extensive work with the country's indigenous communities and his efforts to safeguard their languages and cultures and assist them in the long process of reclaiming their rights as peoples. Professor Lemus has published numerous books and articles related to language revitalization, theoretical linguistics, and the Spanish language, as well as textbooks for learning endangered languages.  One of his most successful grassroots projects is the early language immersion program for children ages 3-5 known as Cuna Nahuat, currently active in three indigenous communities in western El Salvador. The program is run by elderly native Pipil Nahua-speaking women. The main objective of the Cuna Nahuat is to form a replacement generation of Nahuat speakers and thus prevent the language from becoming extinct.

Geneva Foster Gluck is a creative researcher, designer and physically trained performer. Her work utilizes immersive event-making and material storytelling to explore a range of topics and experiences often grounded in post-colonial, feminist, and ecological approaches. Geneva currently lives in Tucson, Arizona where she is working on a fem-western, hand-made batteries, and other performing objects.

Rajiv Gupta is a Distinguished Professor and Amrik Singh Poonian Professor of Computer Science at UC Riverside where he is a member of the RIPLE research group. His research interests include: Programming, Compiler, Runtime & Architectural Support for Parallel & Distributed Heterogeneous Systems; and Software Tools for Monitoring and Managing Runtime Behavior. He has coauthored 316 papers with an h-index of 66 and over 15,500 citations. He is a coinventor of 9 US patents. Rajiv has supervised PhD dissertations of 36 students including the following two winners of the ACM SIGPLAN Outstanding Doctoral Dissertation Award in Programming Languages -- (2009) Xiangyu Zhang, Purdue Univ. and (2001) Rastislav Bodik, Univ. of Washington. Five of his advisees are recipients of the prestigious NSF CAREER Award. Papers coauthored by Rajiv with his students have been selected for: inclusion in 20 Years of PLDI (1979-1999),  SIGSOFT distinguished paper award in ICSE 2003, best paper award in PACT 2010, best paper award in HiPC 2020, best student paper award in LCPC 2015, the most original paper award in ICPP 2003, and outstanding paper award in ICECCS 1996. He received the UCR Doctoral Dissertation Advisor/Mentor Award (2012).

Rajiv is a Fellow of the ACM (2009), the IEEE (2008), and the AAAS (2011). He is a recipient of the NSF's Presidential Young Investigator Award (1991). Rajiv served on the Technical Advisory Group on Networking and Information Technology created by the US President's Council of Advisors on Science and Technology (PCAST) during its review of the Federal NITRD Program (2006-2007). He served as the Conference Chair for FCRC 2015; General Chair for PPoPP'20, ASPLOS'11 and PLDI'08 conferences; and Co-General Chair for ASPLOS'24 and CGO'05 conferences. He also served as the Program Chair for PLDI'03, HPCA'03, LCTES'05, and CC'10 conferences; Program Co-Chair for CC'21 and HiPEAC'08 conference; and Program Vice-Chair for HiPC'03 conference. Rajiv has served on program committees of major conferences in PL/Compilers & Computer Architecture including PLDI, POPL, PPoPP, CGO, ISCA, ASPLOS, MICRO, HPCA, ICS, ICDCS, PACT & HiPEAC. He served as an Associate Editor for ACM TACO & IEEE TC, and is currently serving on the boards of Parallel Computing & Computer Languages journals.

biography: Elmi Muller is a South African health care leader and transplant surgeon. She has extensive experience as a leader and advisor in several national and international professional societies and organizations. She has worked and trained clinicians in Africa through the ISN Educational Ambassador’s programme and had been involved in several workshops of the World Health Organisation. She is currently a member of the WHO Taskforce for Organ Donation and Transplantation. Her research on HIV positive-to-positive transplantation had a transformative impact on policy, service delivery and society in general, as it redefined practices and beliefs in the field of transplantation.  For this work she was awarded the College of Fellows Research Award of the University of Cape Town in October 2010, the Checkers-Shoprite Women of the Year award in 2011, the Women in Transplant Hero award of The Transplantation Society in 2016 and the Alan Pifer Research Award at the University of Cape Town in 2019. Between January 2017 and December 2021 she was the Chair and Head of the Division of General Surgery at the University of Cape Town. On 1 January 2022, she took up the position of Dean at Stellenbosch University's Faculty of Medicine and Health Science. She holds an A1 NRF Research rating in South Africa. In September 2022 she became the President of the international Transplantation Society (TTS).

Dr. Yost is the University Professor and Head of Analytical Chemistry at the University of Florida.  He is recognized internationally as a leader in the field of analytical chemistry, particularly tandem mass spectrometry (MS/MS).  Dr. Yost received his BS degree in Chemistry in 1974 from the University of Arizona, having performed undergraduate research in chromatography with Professor Mike Burke and his PhD degree in Analytical Chemistry in 1979 from Michigan State University, having performed graduate research with Professor Chris Enke.  He then joined the faculty of the University of Florida.  

Dr. Yost's professional activities have focused on research and teaching in analytical mass spectrometry and metabolomics.  His group’s research has reflected a unique balance between instrumentation development, fundamental studies, and applications.  His group has led in the application of novel mass spectrometric methods and techniques to areas such as metabolomics, clinical, biomedical, pharmaceutical, environmental, petrochemical, and forensic chemistry.  He is best known as the co-inventor of the triple quadrupole mass spectrometer, perhaps the most common mass spectrometer today, with annual sales of over $1B.  Every year over 10 million newborns are tested for inherited illnesses using that instrument, saving 100,000 of them from death or serious illness. 

Dr. Yost has supervised the research of over 120 graduate students during the past 43 years, graduating 100 PhDs from his group.  He has served as PI or Co-PI on grants and contracts totaling over $65M of funding.  Research in the group has led to over 235 publications and 20 patents.  He still loves teaching undergraduates and graduates in the classroom.  Dr. Yost recently completed terms on the Florida Board of Governors (Regents) and the University of Florida Board of Trustees. 

Dr. Yost directs the Southeast Center for Integrated Metabolomics (SECIM) as well as NIH’s nationwide Metabolomics Consortium.  He is also a Professor of Pathology at both the University of Florida and the University of Utah/ARUP.  His research has been recognized with the 1993 ASMS Award for Distinguished Contribution in Mass Spectrometry, the 2018 MSACL Award for Distinguished Contribution to Clinical Mass Spectrometry, the 2019 CPSA Distinguished Analytical Scientist Award, the 2019 Florida Academy of Sciences Medal, and the 2021 Pittsburgh Analytical Chemistry Award.  He has also received the Distinguished Eagle Scout Award.  Dr. Yost was inducted into the Florida Inventors Hall of Fame in 2019 and was named a Fellow of the National Academy of Inventors in 2021.  He currently serves as Past President of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry (ASMS).

My Ph.D. was conferred in anthropology with an emphasis in geosciences from the University of Arizona. I define myself as a transdisciplinary and interdisciplinary researcher, where my work wickedly combines anthropology, paleo- and modern ecology, geochemistry, biochemistry, modeling, and comparative vertebrate and non-vertebrate osteology. My research focus has the ultimate goal of informing modern policy and practice in our world by understanding the nature of coupled human-ecological systems in the past and the resiliency of such systems during climate and environmental change. I am a four field approach anthropological archaeologist, with specialties spanning our sub-disciplines, and I have collaborated with, advised, and/or mentored in three subfields: cultural, biological/physical, and archaeology.

Osamu Tsutsumi is currently the Professor of Polymer Materials Chemistry at Ritsumeikan University. Dr. Tsutsumi obtained a Bachelor of Engineering in Applied Chemistry from the Kumamoto University in 1993 and his Doctorate from Tokyo Institute of Technology (TokyoTech) in 1998, where he was also a JSPS research fellow. Dr. Tsutsumi was a postdoctoral researcher in Dr. Seth Marder’s group at California Institute of Technology (Caltech) and at the University of Arizona from 1998–1999. After staying in the US, he moved to the Chemical Resources Laboratory, TokyoTech, where he was an Assistant Professor from 1999–2002. He joined Ebara Research Co., Ltd. as a Research Scientist from 2003–2007. He was also a lecturer at the Tokyo University of Science from 2002–2007. In 2007, Dr. Tsutsumi moved to the Department of Applied Chemistry at Ritsumeikan University where he was appointed an Associate Professor of Polymer Materials Chemistry.

I am a condensed matter spectroscopist and my current research interests include study of structure and dynamics of lipid membrane biophysics with lipid-protein interactions, synthesis and characterization of ferromagnetic nano materials to study their structure and phase compositions, and study of optical and electrical properties of oxy halide and telluride glass (amorphous) systems. Major spectroscopic technique being used is multi-nuclear solid-state NMR including zero field (internal filed) NMR along with complimentary techniques like Raman spectroscopy, x-ray, IR, scanning probe microscopy(SEM) and VSM (magnetic properties), DSC, TGA, dielectric studies.
Wildlife and Conservation Biology Researcher for the Department of Forestry and Natural Resources at University of Kentucky, and Research Associate - Biostatistician at University of Arizona.

Robert M. Cutler is Senior Researcher, Institute of European, Russian and Eurasian Studies, Carleton University; Senior Research Fellow in Energy Security, NATO Association of Canada; Senior Fellow, Canada International Council; and Fellow, Canadian Energy Research Institute. He earned two Bachelor's degrees at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, a Master's degree at Pennsylvania State University, and the Ph.D. at The University of Michigan. Also he held pre- and post-doctoral fellowships at the University of Geneva's Graduate Institute of International Studies (Gallatin Fellow, HEI), Moscow State University (IREX Fellow) and Columbia University (Mellon Fellow, Harriman Institute).
He has held many competitive grants and fellowships and has been on the editorial board of numerous academic and policy journals in his fields. Besides extensive journalism on-line and in print, he has published over 50 peer-refereed articles and book chapters as well as two books. After a dozen years exclusively in universities, he expanded into policy analysis and consulting.
He is best known for his expertise as an Energy Security & Geo-economics Specialist, and also as a Strategic Communications Specialist & Media Analyst as well as a Complex Organization & Decision Specialist. He has written expert affidavits on human-rights conditions in various Asian countries, for appeals of immigration refusals of applications for refugee status, never yet losing a case.

Matthew Harp is an Associate Librarian for Research Data Services and Outreach in the Open and Science and Scholarly Communications division of the Arizona State University Library. Matthew received his Master's Degree in Information Resources and Library Science in 2013, his Graduate Certificate in Digital Information Management in 2011, and his Bachelor's of Fine Arts in Media Arts in 1998 from the University of Arizona. He specializes in open scholarship and research services specializing in data management and sharing and facilitates the curation of the ASU Research Data Repository. Before becoming a librarian, Matthew worked as the Digital Library Projects Manager at the ASU Library for 14 years producing podcasts and video programs. He is a 2010 Library Journal Mover and Shaker.

Professor and Director of the School of Journalism at the University of Arizona. Director of the Master in Bilingual Journalism and affiliated Faculty with the Center for Latin American Studies and the Human Rights Practice Program.
Retis holds a Major in Communications (University of Lima, Peru), a Master's in Latin American Studies (National Autonomous University of Mexico), and a Ph.D. in Contemporary Latin America (Complutense University of Madrid, Spain).
Prior to entering academia, she worked for more than two decades as a journalist in Peru, Mexico, and Spain in various print and broadcast media outlets. She has three decades of teaching experience in various universities in the United States, Spain, and Mexico.
Her areas of research include Latin America, international migration, diasporas, transnational communities; cultural industries; ethnic media; diversity and the media; Latino media in Europe, North America, and Asia; bilingual journalism, journalism studies, and journalism education.
Retis joined the University of Arizona in 2019. That year she was awarded the Provost Investment Fund (PIF) to launch the M.A. in Bilingual Journalism, Cultural Competence and Innovation. In 2021 she was awarded the title of Center for University Education Scholarship, CUES Distinguished Fellow for her research project “Bilingual Journalism Education in the United States: Development, Implementation, and Assessment."
From 2008 to 2019 she worked as Associate Professor in the interdisciplinary Minor of Spanish-language Journalism and Master in Communications programs at California State University. She has been visiting scholar at the University of Tokyo, Florida International University, City University London, New York University, London School of Economics, and University of Westminster, among others.
Recent books include: Communicative Spaces in Bilingual Contexts: Discourses, Synergies and Counterflows in Spanish and English (Routledge, 2022), Reporting on Latin/a/x Communities: A Guide for Journalists (Routledge, 2022), Narratives of Migration, Relocation and Belonging: Latin Americans in London (Palgrave, 2020), The Handbook of Diasporas, Media and Culture (Willey, 2019). 
Recent book chapters include “Migrations and the Media between Asia and Latin America: Japanese-Brazilians in Tokyo and São Paulo” (Sage, 2019), “Hashtag Jóvenes Latinos: Challenges and opportunities of teaching civic advocacy journalism in ‘glocal’ contexts” (Peter Lang, 2018), “The transnational restructuring of communication and consumption practices. Latinos in the urban settings of global cities” (Routledge, 2017). “Underrepresented Majorities: Latin@s and the Media in the Digital Age” (Routledge, 2017), “Latino Diasporas and the Media. Interdisciplinary Approaches to Understand Transnationalism and Communications in Global Cities” (Wiley, 2014).
Recent reports include: Hispanic Media Today. Serving Bilingual and Bicultural Audiences in the Digital Age (Democracy Fund, 2019), La circulación de la cultura en español en las ciudades globales de los Estados Unidos: Los Ángeles, Nueva York, Miami (Hispanic Cultural Circuits in Urban Context of Global Cities: Los Angeles, New York, Miami) (RIE, 2019), and Los Latinos y las industrias culturales en español en Estados Unidos (Latinos and Spanish-language Cultural Industries in the U.S.) (RIE, 2015).  
Recent reports include: Hispanic Media Today. Serving Bilingual and Bicultural Audiences in the Digital Age (Democracy Fund, 2019), Hispanic Cultural Circuits in Urban Context of Global Cities: New York, Miami, and Los Angeles (RIE, 2019). Latinos and Spanish-language Cultural Industries in the United States (RIE, 2015), Exploratory Research on Cultural Consumption of Latino Immigrants in Spain: transnational context of cultural practices (Fundación Alternativas, 2011).
Twitter: @jretis

Denice Adkins is a professor at the School of Information Science & Learning Technologies, University of Missouri, and co-editor of Journal of Education for Library & Information Science. She is currently serving as Membership Director of the Association for Library and Information Science Education and Treasurer for REFORMA (The National Association to Promote Library & Information Services to Latinos and the Spanish-Speaking).  Her past experiences include a Fulbright Scholarship to Honduras, a Fulbright Specialist to India, serving as president of REFORMA, secretary-treasurer of ALISE, and councilor-at-large for the American Library Association. Her research interests include public libraries, services to the Latinx/Latine community, and services for diverse library users.

Sarah Maxwell earned her Ph.D. in public policy from George Mason University. She is currently Assistant Provost, Office of Community College Relations and Associate Professor in Public Policy Public and Nonprofit Management at the University of Texas at Dallas, with a focus on health policy and disease surveillance. She previously served as Associate Dean, Office of the Executive Vice President; Associate Dean, Office of Undergraduate Education; and Assistant Dean, School of Economic, Political and Policy Sciences. 

Her numerous refereed articles and book chapters focus on nonprofit organizations and youth development with a more recent interest in tick-borne illness, chronic disease, and health policy. Dr. Maxwell is also engaged in health initiatives for vulnerable populations, receiving a grant from the Rita & Alex Hillman Foundation to assess tick-borne illness as an occupational hazard among migrant and seasonal farm workers. She also received funding to provide an educational social media campaign on Lyme Disease. Dr. Maxwell authored a book titled, Success and solitude: Feminist organizations fifty years after the Feminine Mystique, and she served as the Principal Investigator under a U.S. Department of Justice grant to provide academic and career-focused mentoring to at-risk youth.  
 
In addition to her academic career, Dr. Maxwell managed $10 million in federal, state, and private grants while working for a national nonprofit organization. During this time, she organized a joint task force between the U.S. Department of Labor and U.S. Department of Justice to study promising employment practices for court-involved youth. She also worked as a consultant to nonprofits and federal contractors, developing best practice and management guidelines for youth offender and youth development practitioners. When she is not writing or teaching, Dr. Maxwell can be found fostering service dogs and serving as an ambassador for the Global Lyme Alliance.
Current research interests focus on the intersection of reference services, organizational culture, and EDI with academic libraries.

Dr. Bill Scott is a Biomedical Engineer who has spent the past 19+ years embedded within healthcare, identifying problems and solutions for the transplant community. He presently works at the Newcastle University Medical school in the Translational and Clinical Research Institute where he helped to establish and serves as Scientific Director for the TRM facility the ‘Transplant Regenerative Medicine’ (TRM) group. Bill is a basic/translational researcher in transplantation and regenerative medicine; particularly focused on understanding changes during the peri-transplant period and developing/assessing novel interventions to overcome these towards increasing utilisation and posttransplant function. To facilitate translation of these findings into clinical practice, Bill has developed a particular focus on improved access to critical research tissues, working with regulatory bodies to adapt to emergent scientific developments, as well as understanding the commercial aspects of clinical translation.
Bill contributes to several national consortia including as a co-Investigator on the NIHR funded ‘Blood and Transplant Research Unit in Organ Donation and Transplantation’ in collaboration with Cambridge University and NHS Blood and Transplant (NHS-BT); Co-Investigator and National Tissue and Cell Processing Coordinator for the Quality in Organ Donation (QUOD) MRC Tissue Bank. Beyond these research activities, Bill also serves as the Module Leader for the Transplantation Master of Research Course at Newcastle University; acts as the Commercialisation Lead for the Regenerative Medicine, Stem Cells, Transplantation Faculty Theme; is a member of the leadership group for the Newcastle University Centre for Excellence in Biomedical Engineering, and contributes to a number of national NHS-BT initiatives related to facilitating transplant-related research. He is active in many societies and is presently serving as an elected board member for the European Society for Organ Transplantation Basic Science Committee. Outside of his academic endeavours, Bill is currently the Chief Scientific Officer for ScubaTx Ltd.; a spin out from Newcastle University focused on developing a medical device for enhanced organ preservation, that meets the real-world constraints of transplant personnel, money, logistics and physical space.

Dr. Zhaohui Wang received his Ph.D. in Electrical and Computer Engineering from the University of Arizona in 2011. He also received Master of Science in Bioengineering from the University of Toledo in 2005, and Master of Science in Mechanical Engineering from the University of Arizona in 2008. From 2011 he continued post-doctoral training in the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center. In 2014, he was promoted to Visiting Assistant Professor of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science at Texas A&M University-Kingsville. His current research includes medical imaging, biosensor, micro/nano-electronics, and energy devices.

Anali Maughan Perry is the Head of the Open Science and Scholarly Communication (OSSC) Division and the Scholarly Communication Librarian at ASU Library. In this role, she leads efforts to provide outreach and education to the ASU community regarding open science and scholarship, scholarly publishing and copyright, with particular emphasis on fair use, open access to scholarly information, and open and affordable education initiatives. The OSSC Division includes Research Data Services and Course Resource Services.

Anali has worked full-time at the ASU Library since 2000. Her previous positions include working in Interlibrary Loan as a Library Specialist and as an acquisitions librarian. She is currently a presenter for the Association for College and Research Libraries Scholarly Communication Roadshow and serves on the steering committee for the Coalition of Open Access Policy Institutions. Anali also moonlighted as the host of The Library Minute video series from 2009-2013.

Sammed Mandape currently works as a bioinformatician at Center for Human Identification (CHI), UNTHSC, Fort Worth, Texas. At CHI, Sammed is invested in developing and optimizing bioinformatics workflows for massive parallel sequencing data, specifically, human nuclear and mitochondrial genome data from human forensic samples. His work focuses on using computational methods to identify unique markers for DNA fingerprinting. His expertise includes sequencing data analysis, applying machine learning methods for biological big data analysis, and developing computational and bioinformatics tools to analyze and interpret omics data. He has led and supported multiple cancer research projects, infectious diseases research, human microbiome profiling, metabolomics, and forensic research. In his previous roles, Sammed has served as a bioinformatician for PCORI (Patient Center Outcome Research Initiative), MeTRC (Meharry Clinical Translational Research Center), Better Algorithms and Chemistry for Mixture Interpretation, MMDIT (Development of Mitochondrial Mixture Database & Interpretation tool). Sammed also serves as editor for Current Trends in Clinical and Medical Sciences Journal and reviews for various scientific publications. Outside work, he likes to spend his free time hiking and exploring new trails.

Laura A. Murray, MSIS, MBA, AHIP is the HCA Graduate Medical Education Librarian Faculty liaising between USF Morsani College of Medicine and the HCA Healthcare West Florida Division hospitals training residents, fellows, and faculty. A member of the faculty at USF Health Libraries, Murray serves residents, fellows, and faculty at HCA Healthcare hospitals across Florida. Focusing on transformational learning and utilizing learning theory, Murray teaches coursework in evidence based practice, search strategy development, in addition to research and literature review planning. Current research is in Graduate Medical Education librarianship, curriculum development, LGBTQ+ in Graduate Medical Education, and change management in an academic-corporate consortium.

Graduate student in Condensed Matter physics with research interests in Quantum Thermodynamics and Statistical Mechanics, Quantum Transport and Mesoscopics, Quantum Information Theory, Nonequilibrium Topological Quantum Matter and Quantum Stochastics.
