I am a licensed clinical health psychologist, Assistant Professor of Medicine, and mental health coordinator for the adult cystic fibrosis team at National Jewish Health in Denver, CO. I also have my PSYPACT license, which allows me to practice telehealth across state lines among states that have enacted and effective legislation allowing for interjurisdictional practice.    My clinical and research expertise surrounds using telehealth and other technology-based interventions to improve health and behavior changes, especially among adults with cystic fibrosis.  Areas of focus include improving management of stress, sleep, anxiety, depression, and interpersonal relationships.  I am currently funded by the Cystic Fibrosis Foundation as the principal investigator of a multi-site randomized controlled trial of my telehealth stress management program called, "Coping and Learning to Manage Stress with Cystic Fibrosis," or CALM for short.  Other institutions involved in this RCT are the University of North Carolina and Johns Hopkins Medicine. 

I completed my PhD in clinical health psychology at the University of Colorado Denver, a MA and EdM in counseling psychology at Columbia University, a MA in clinical psychology from the University of Colorado Denver, and a BA in psychology at the University of Michigan.

I have a PhD from Department of Plant Pathology, Faculty of Agriculture Sciences, University of the Punjab Lahore, Pakistan, and my Ph.D. thesis was on the “Genetic diversity of begomoviruses affecting diverse host plants in Peri-urban areas of Lahore''. I have worked on the molecular and biological characterization of begomoviruses and their DNA-satellites infecting in diverse host plants, construction of infectious clones of begomoviruses and their associated DNA-satellites for agrobacterium mediated inoculation in the experimental model plant Nicotiana benthamiana. These clones were also used to conduct biolistic inoculation experiments to fulfill Koch’s postulates in Dr. Judith Brown’s Lab at the University of Arizona, Tucson. Confirmation and evaluation of infectivity assays was done in the inoculated N. benthamiana plants using PCR, RT-PCR and Southern blot hybridization. I have hands on experience on various molecular biology techniques including PCR, RCA, restriction digestion, sequencing and sequence analysis, Standard Demarcation Tool (SDT) used for geminivirus taxonomy and species demarcation, phylogenetic studies, recombination analysis, construction of infectious clones, biolistic inoculation experiments and infectivity assays. Many first and novel reports are reported during my research work, in a wide range of plant species for the first time from Pakistan and also have expertise in molecular characterization of fungal as well as bacterial genome.
      I have served as faculty member in different organizations, currently representing UVAS, Lahore.  I received nationally competitive DPCC grants (Doctoral Program Coordination Committee) and IRSIP-HEC fellowship (Higher Education Commission- International Research Support Initiative Program) and carried out part of my PhD research in School of Plant Sciences, University of Arizona, Tucson. I have presented oral and poster presentations at International conferences, and won 1st and 2nd place awards. I am also active member of organizing international conferences, cabinet member of Pakistan Phytopathological society (councilor) and also reviewers of the journals.

Dr. Daniel Kilper is a professor and innovator whose research is aimed at solving fundamental and real-world problems in communication networks in order to create a faster, more affordable, and energy-efficient Internet, addressing interdisciplinary challenges for smart cities, sustainability, and digital equity. Within both academia and industry, he has made pioneering contributions in communication devices and systems research, primarily spanning three areas: energy-efficient communication networks, optical performance monitoring, and software-defined optical networking.

Researcher Ph.D. in management who works effectively in teams or independently. More than 13 years working in the development, implementation, management, and delivery of projects in the capital goods, pneumatics, logistics, and clinical trials sectors. All projects were completed on time, within budget, and to the satisfaction of stakeholders. Currently, I hold the position of junior researcher in the artificial intelligence department, developing a management model for the university-industry technology transfer process. Expertise in regulatory institutions, informal institutions, public policies, legitimacy of companies through identity, value chain, and organizational structure adaptation, innovation in business model, institutional and organizational capabilities, technological transfer process, and qualitative and quantitative methods.

Dr. Beatrice Krauss, Ph.D., Social-Personality, The Graduate Center of the City University of New York, M.A., Clinical Psychology, University of Kansas, is an Associate Editor of the Journal of Methods and Measurement in the Social Sciences, a Richard L. Gorsuch Postdoctoral Fellow, and a Designated Campus Colleague for the psychology department at University of Arizona. She consults on research issues and methodology throughout University of Arizona, notably with the Mel and Enid Zuckerman College of Public Health. She is an Emerita Professor of the City University of New York Graduate School of Public Health and Health Policy. Until 2012, she was the Executive Director of the Hunter College Center for Community and Urban Health. 

Dr. Krauss has been involved with over 40 privately-, city-, state-, nationally- or internationally-funded research projects regarding family and community adjustment to health threats. Her most recent award as a Principal Investigator is for a Scoping Review of the Literature on Cognitive Bias in Medical Diagnosis, awarded by Division 9 of the American Psychological Association. Until May 2012, Dr. Krauss co-chaired the Non-Governmental Organization Committee on HIV/AIDS for organizations in consultative status to the Economic and Social Council of the United Nations. She completed an NIMH-funded program to mentor a new generation of HIV researchers in 2013, and completed a year as a visiting investigator at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, transferring insights about the destigmatization of HIV to lung cancer in 2011. Dr. Krauss is a Fellow of the Health Psychology Division of the American Psychological Association. She is also a harpist; she plays as a therapeutic musician at Casa de la Luz Hospice in Tucson, AZ.

Chris Jenks is a professor of law and teaches criminal law, evidence and the law of armed conflict. He also serves as a consultant for the Department of Defense Office of the General Counsel, a research fellow at the Program on the Regulation of Emerging Military Technology in Australia and as member of the Council for International Institute of Humanitarian Law in Sanremo, Italy.

Professor Jenks’ research interests are at the intersection of the law of armed conflict, accountability norms and emerging technology. He is the co-author of a law of armed conflict textbook and has published book chapters with both Oxford and Cambridge University Presses.  His articles have appeared in the law reviews and journals of Harvard, Berkeley, Georgetown, Stanford, & Washington & Lee and the International Review of the Red Cross. His blog posts have been featured on Lawfare, Just Security, and Opinio Juris.  He has published opeds with both USA Today and Newsweek.  He has presented to House and Senate Staffers on Capitol Hill, at the American Society of International Law, the Council on Foreign Relations, and at universities and institutes around the world.

In 2020 he testified at a Commission on Security Cooperation in Europe hearing on Artificial Weapons and Autonomous Systems. In 2019, he worked with both the Defense Innovation Board and the National Security Commission on Artificial Intelligence.  Between 2017-2018, while on leave from SMU and serving as the Special Counsel to the General Counsel for the Department of Defense, Professor Jenks twice served on the U.S. delegation to the United Nations Group of Governmental Experts meetings on Lethal Autonomous Weapons in Geneva, Switzerland.  He previously presented on autonomous weapons at a similar United Nations meeting. In 2015, he was awarded a Fulbright Senior Scholars Grant to research autonomous weapons as part of a multidisciplinary research group based out of Melbourne, Australia. In 2014, he served on a working group on the environment and armed conflict at the United Nations in New York organized by the Special Rapporteur for the International Law Commission. And in 2013, he served as a consultant to the Office of the Secretary of Defense on security sector reform in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.

Prior to joining the SMU faculty, Professor Jenks served for more than 20 years in the U.S. military, first as an infantry officer and later as a judge advocate and was detailed to the human rights and refugees section of the Office of the Legal Adviser at the Department of State and as a Special Assistant U.S. Attorney on both the civil and criminal side at the Department of Justice.

The Department of Justice’s Counterterrorism Section nominated him for the John Marshall Award for interagency cooperation following his work as the lead prosecutor in the Army’s first counterterrorism trial involving a soldier who attempted to aid the al-Qaeda terrorist network. While working at the Department of State, he served as a member of the U.S. delegation to the Third Committee of the United Nations General Assembly. In his last assignment, Professor Jenks served as the chief of the international law branch for the U.S. Army in the Pentagon, where he supervised the program by which foreign countries asserted criminal jurisdiction over U.S. service members and represented the Department of Defense at Status of Forces Agreement negotiations; he was also the legal adviser to the U.S. military observers group, which provides personnel to U.N. missions around the world.

Merc Fox is an NSF Merit Review Panel Fellow, a Communities of Practice Fellow with the Online Ethics Center, a Fulbright Specialist in data diplomacy, and the founding director of the Center of Excellence in Data for Society, CODATA's first policy research institute.  Merc leads international data diplomacy initiatives, promotes the rights and responsibilities of individuals through innovative data governance, develops provocative projects that expand the role of data assets in society, and builds international networks of cross-functional stakeholders to advance Data in Society frameworks.  Merc facilitates interdisciplinary dialogues in public policy, professional standards, and best practices while contributing thought leadership related to the enduring and emerging cultural, social, and ethical challenges that data technologies pose.  Mx. Fox further leverages special expertise in data diplomacy and collaboratory cultures to advance multilateral science cooperation through an STS practitioner approach.
